  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Gavi Health System Strengthening Programme of the Government of South Sudan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the country&#x2019;s independence in 2011, the protracted conflict in South Sudan has left the country&#x2019;s health system fragile and unable to address the growing and diverse needs of its population, including that of women and children with very poor and limited infrastructure which remain largely inaccessible to most of the population, including nearly 2 million internally displaced persons (IDPs). This situation is exacerbated by flooding during the six-month rainy season and a severe lack of human resources for health (qualified health care workers). Thus, the country has not been able to meet maternal, new-born and child health care needs, including those related to immunization reflecting a low routine immunization coverage with only 60 percent of children aged under 1 being reported as having received the Penta3 vaccination in 2020, a slight increase from 2019 at 44%. IOM, through the Health Systems strengthening support to the ministry of Health project aims to contribute to increased routine immunization coverage of children 0 to 23 months through scaling up of vaccination services to IDPs, returnees, conflict affected host communities in hard -to-reach locations by strengthening vaccine last mile delivery, service delivery and improved data management.</narrative>
  </description>
